</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Note then when a new major version of an API is required, the ne=
w major version MUST include all operations and associated functionality fr=
om the prior version except where this functionality is deliberately being =
deprecated in the new version.</strong></p>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignStandards-MaturityLevels">Maturity Levels</h3>
<p>Whilst being "properly" RESTful requires compliance to a number of archi=
tectural style guides and patterns,&nbsp;what we are trying to achieve with=
 APIs is more important than ivory tower arguments about levels of complian=
ce with the RESTful style guides.&nbsp;That said, the following link provid=
es a good description of a maturity model for Restful APIs which takes a co=
arse grained approach to defining increasing levels of maturity, and how th=
is benefits the integrating systems:&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://martinfowler.co=
m/articles/richardsonMaturityModel.html" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nof=
ollow">http://martinfowler.com/articles/richardsonMaturityModel.html</a></p=
>
<p>The following table summarises the Richardson Maturity Model:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Level</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Description</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>"The&nbsp;Swamp of POX/POJ"</p><p>HTTP is use=
d as the transport, but without using any of the web mechanisms. Effectivel=
y, this is XML or JSON remote procedure calls (Plain old XML/JSON).</p></td=
>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>1</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Resources</p><p>Rather than making all reques=
ts to a singular service endpoint, we now start talking to individual resou=
rces.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>2</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>HTTP Verbs</p><p>Start&nbsp; using the HTTP v=
erbs as closely as possible to how they are used in HTTP itself</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>3</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Hypermedia Controls</p><p>Introduce Hypermedi=
a As The Engine Of Application State - The message flow defines the availab=
le behaviour on the resource - "What can one do next?"</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>There is a lot more to maturity than just this, as one could argue that:=
</p>
<p>Level 1 should introduce some additional&nbsp;standards&nbsp;for using r=
esources, but the key is to start treating endpoints as managing resources,=
 not providing services, in order to allow the next step to work.</p>
<p>Level 2 should cover off some of the other core HTTP behavior management=
 capabilities, especially around caching, but the key is at this level we a=
re driving the message flow behaviour in line with how the web's client ser=
ver model works.</p>
<p>Level 3 is nirvana and challenging to implement fully with APIs.</p>
<p>For Westpac Mesh APIs, we are targeting level 2 compliance and will supp=
ort level 3 (HATEOAS) for use cases where it makes sense to do so.&nbsp; Th=
e precise design model which will be used to support HATEOAS is yet to be f=
inalised.</p>
<p><br></p>
